						               													<description>&amp;#9;&amp;#9;&amp;#9;&amp;#9;&amp;#10;&amp;#9;&amp;#9;&amp;#9;&amp;#9;&amp;#10;&amp;#9;&amp;#9;&amp;#9;&amp;#9;&amp;#9;Polar&amp;#10;&amp;#10;&amp;#10;     Square board, 9x9 or 11x11 or 13x13&amp;#10;     Black and white pieces&amp;#10;&amp;#10;&amp;#10;&amp;#9;&amp;#9;&amp;#9;&amp;#9;&amp;#10;&amp;#9;&amp;#9;&amp;#9;&amp;#9;&amp;#10;&amp;#9;&amp;#9;&amp;#9;&amp;#9;&amp;#9;Rules&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Pieces are placed on empty intersections of the board. Connections are orthogonal only.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The board is initially empty.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;One of the players takes two pieces (black and white) and places them on any arbitrary adjacent spaces. The other player may now decide on which color to play.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Black starts, then players take turns placing one of their pieces on an empty space according to the following rules.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Connected pieces form a group, and same-colored connected pieces within a group are called a section. A group may never consist of more than two sections.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Player may only pass if they have no moves left. They must play again in a successive turn when moves are available again.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The game ends when both players have to pass.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;&amp;#9;&amp;#9;&amp;#9;&amp;#9;&amp;#10;&amp;#9;&amp;#9;&amp;#9;&amp;#9;&amp;#10;&amp;#9;&amp;#9;&amp;#9;&amp;#9;&amp;#9;Score&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Groups with one or equally sized sections score zero points. For any other group, the player holding the majority section gets the triangular number section points: &amp;#10;T(n) = n*(n+1)/2&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The player with the highest total score wins. Games can end in a draw.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
